181 postsecondary employee in excess of two percent, except as
182 specifically provided in this act.
183 (5) Miscellaneous provisions. The following provisions
184 are hereby established:
185 a. Fiscal Year. All salaries and salary increases that
186 are established by the State Board of Education shall be paid
187 in full to each person employed before the end of the
188 applicable fiscal year as defined in Section 16-1-1 of the
189 Code of Alabama 1975, as amended.
190 b. Extended Work. Public K-12 school employees on
191 contracts that extend beyond 187 days, or the hourly
192 equivalent thereof, shall be given a pro rata salary increment
193 for each or partial day of work extending beyond 187 days.
194 c. Local Increment. Any cost-of-living adjustment
195 and/or increase on the State Minimum Salary Schedule for
196 teachers as provided in this act shall be exclusive of any
Page 7

teachers as provided in this act shall be exclusive of any
HB239 Enrolled
197 local pay increase granted or due to teachers under provisions
198 of any local salary schedule. Any cost-of-living adjustment
199 and/or pay increase required by this act for public school
200 support personnel shall be in addition to any pay increase due
201 or granted to the employee under provisions of any local
202 salary schedules. The pay increase provisions of this act
203 shall not apply to any salary supplements granted by local
204 boards of education, bonuses earned for certification by the
205 National Board of Professional Teaching Standards, or the
206 federal portion of the salary paid to a Junior Reserve Officer
207 Training Corps (JROTC) instructor employed by a local school
208 board.
209 d. Community Education. Each county and city board of
210 education shall have the option to exclude from the provisions
211 of this act any part-time employees of community education or
212 school-sponsored child care or child enrichment program that
213 is supplemental to the state-required educational program.
214 e. Local Chief Executive Officers. The pay increase
215 provisions of this act shall not apply to superintendents of
216 education of any school system or institution. Any pay
217 increase given to the superintendent shall be by majority
218 recorded vote of the governing body or authority.
219 Section 2. The pay increase granted in Section 1 of
220 this act shall begin in fiscal year 2026-2027 and continue in
221 subsequent years. Nothing in this act shall authorize
222 additional pay increases in subsequent years.
223 Section 3. (a) There is provided for fiscal year
224 2026-2027 a funded one-time, lump-sum payment, hereinafter
Page 8

2026-2027 a funded one-time, lump-sum payment, hereinafter
HB239 Enrolled
225 referred to as "longevity bonus payment," to each individual
226 whose effective date of retirement for purposes of receiving
227 benefits from the Teachers' Retirement System is prior to May
228 1, 2026, and is receiving, or is entitled to receive, a
229 monthly allowance from the Teachers' Retirement System on
230 September 30, 2026.
231 (b) The formula for calculating the longevity bonus
232 payment shall be one dollar ($1) per month for each year of
233 service attained by the retiree.
234 (c) Beneficiaries of deceased members or deceased
235 retirees, if the beneficiary is receiving or is entitled to
236 receive a monthly allowance from the Teachers' Retirement
237 System on September 30, 2026, shall receive a longevity bonus
238 payment of one dollar ($1) per month for each year of service
239 of the deceased member or deceased retiree.
240 (d) For purposes of this section, service includes the
241 service under Section 16-25-1 and Article 9, commencing with
242 Section 16-25-150, Chapter 25, Title 16, Code of Alabama 1975.
243 (e) Any individual who received benefits under the
244 Medicaid program, and whose eligibility for Medicaid benefits
245 would be impaired by the longevity bonus payment provided by
246 this section, shall not be entitled to receive the
247 aforementioned increase. Any individual who subsequently
248 applies for benefits under the Medicaid program, and that
249 individual's eligibility to receive benefits is impaired by
250 the longevity bonus payment provided by this section, shall
251 not be entitled to receive the increase subsequent to the date
252 that the member files application for benefits under the
Page 9

that the member files application for benefits under the
HB239 Enrolled
253 Medicaid program.
254 (f) The longevity bonus payments provided under this
255 section shall be paid to all eligible recipients by the
256 Teachers' Retirement System in October 2026.
257 (g) It is not the intent of this act to make
258 appropriations, but the amount required to pay the cost of the
259 lump-sum payments provided under Section 3 of this act shall
260 be appropriated to the Teachers' Retirement System in HB238 of
261 the 2026 Regular Session.
262 Section 4. The provisions of this act are severable. If
263 any part of this act is declared invalid or unconstitutional,
264 that declaration shall not affect the part that remains.
265 Section 5. This act shall become effective on October
266 1, 2026.
